      <div class="vd-video-caption">
        <div class="vd-figcap"><b>Demonstrated</b>First half: standard plastic claw clip. Second half: the Velvy "D" — flat, flush, no pressure point.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Product worn at home -->
    <div class="vd-fig">
      <div class="vd-wrap">
        <img src="{{ img_product_in }}" alt="Velvy D tortoise holding a low chignon, back of head view" loading="lazy">
        <div class="vd-figcap"><b>Worn</b>The Velvy "D" tortoise — flat against the back of a half-up style. Worn at the wheel, photographed at golden hour.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="vd-wrap">

      <p>I will admit something. When I started this piece, I expected a story about a marketing gimmick. I have written about enough hair-care launches to know what those look like. The first time I clipped a Velvy "D" into my own hair, I was prepared to be unimpressed. <strong>The second time I leaned back against my car seat, I noticed the absence.</strong> The small, dull pressure I had been carrying without knowing it was gone.</p>

      <div class="vd-pull">
        <div class="vd-pull-text">"I noticed the absence. The small dull pressure I had been carrying without knowing it was gone."</div>
        <div class="vd-pull-attr">— L.M., reporting</div>
      </div>

      <p>The reader response has been similar. One woman who wrote in after the original publication, Eloise B., commutes ninety minutes each way in London traffic. "I never noticed how much my head hurt by Friday until I switched," she wrote. "It's not subtle — it's gone." Another, Camille D., a chemist in Lyon, sent two sentences: <em>"My partner is a paramedic. He told me to stop wearing the big plastic ones in the car."</em> She made the switch a month later.</p>

      <p>The product is currently <a href="#vdShop">listed on the brand's site here</a>. There is no retail equivalent — for the moment, at least.</p>

    </div>

